"""
MKT Context Commentary — Matthew chapter 26
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-matthew-26-26.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/matthew.json
- data/commentary/mkt-context/matthew.json (pre-existing: 26:3, 26:17)

Key decisions in this range:
- Passover timing: "two days before Passover" (Nisan 12/13); tension with John's chronology noted
- Anointing at Bethany: alabaster flask / spikenard; 300 denarii = ~year's wages
- 30 pieces of silver = slave-goring price (Exod 21:32); fulfills Zech 11:12-13
- Hallel (Ps 115-118) sung at seder end before departing; Zech 13:7 cited explicitly
- Gethsemane = gat-shmanim (oil press) on western slope of Mount of Olives
- Cup as fate/suffering metaphor throughout OT (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17-22; Jer 25:15)
- Legion = ~6,000 soldiers; 12 legions = 72,000 (one per disciple)
- Tearing of high priest's robes: prescribed response to blasphemy (m. Sanhedrin 7:5)
- "Power" (hē dynamis) as Jewish circumlocution for the divine Name
- Peter's Galilean accent as identifying marker in the courtyard
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "26": {
    "1": '<p>The fifth and final closing formula of Matthew\'s five-discourse structure: "When Jesus had finished all these sayings (<em>tous logous toutous pantas</em>)" — the same formula closing the Sermon on the Mount (7:28), the Mission Discourse (11:1), the Parables Discourse (13:53), the Community Discourse (19:1), and now the Olivet Discourse. The word <em>pantas</em> (all) is unique to this final instance, signaling that the discourse sequence is complete. The Gospel now pivots wholly to the passion narrative.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"You know that after two days the Passover is coming, and the Son of Man will be delivered up to be crucified" — the fifth passion prediction (see 16:21; 17:22-23; 20:18-19; 26:2) explicitly names crucifixion and ties it to Passover timing. "Two days" places this on Nisan 12 or 13, depending on counting conventions. The Synoptic chronology places the Last Supper on Nisan 14 (Passover); John\'s Gospel has Jesus crucified on Nisan 14 as the lambs are being slaughtered — a continuing historical and theological debate.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The plot "to arrest Jesus by stealth and kill him" (<em>dolo kratēsōsin kai apokteinōsin</em>) — <em>dolos</em> (guile, trickery) signals that the leaders recognize they cannot act openly without provoking the Passover crowd. The stealth requirement drives the plot toward Judas\'s offer (v.14-16), which provides exactly what they need: insider knowledge of where Jesus could be found privately. The leaders\' constraint (fear of the crowd) is the structural catalyst for Judas\'s role.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Not during the feast, lest there be an uproar among the people" (<em>thorybos en tō laō</em>) — the Passover festival brought 100,000+ pilgrims to Jerusalem (Josephus estimates higher; the numbers are debated). The Roman prefect (Pilate) brought additional troops from Caesarea Maritima precisely because the festival was the highest-risk period for civil unrest. The leaders\' self-imposed constraint is politically rational: messianic excitement and nationalist sentiment ran highest at Passover, making public action against a popular figure maximally dangerous.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Now when Jesus was at Bethany in the house of Simon the Leper" — Bethany was a village on the eastern slope of the Mount of Olives, approximately two miles from Jerusalem, where Jesus regularly lodged during Passion Week (21:17). Simon the Leper is otherwise unknown; the designation may mean a healed leper who retained the nickname, or it may be a patronymic. The event is placed in the week before the crucifixion; John\'s parallel (John 12:1-8) places it six days before Passover, and John identifies the woman as Mary of Bethany.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"A woman came up to him with an alabaster flask of very expensive ointment (<em>myrou barytimou</em>), and she poured it on his head as he reclined at table" — the alabaster flask was a luxury container; alabaster (calcium carbonate) was mined in Egypt and valued for preserving perfume. Mark 14:3 identifies the ointment as <em>nardos pistikē</em> (pure/genuine nard, or spikenard — an expensive aromatic from the Himalayan region of India). John 12:3 values it at 300 denarii (approximately a year\'s wages). Pouring it on the head is an anointing gesture with royal and priestly associations.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"And when the disciples saw it, they were indignant, saying, \'Why this waste?\'" — the disciples\' objection frames the act in the patron-client economy of almsgiving: 300 denarii\' worth of ointment poured out in a single moment is an extraordinary use of resources that could feed many poor persons. Their indignation is not malicious; it reflects the standard application of Jewish piety priorities (care for the poor as a primary obligation). The objection is immediately reframed by Jesus as a failure to perceive the moment\'s unique significance.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"For this could have been sold for a large sum and given to the poor" (<em>prachthēnai pollou kai dothēnai ptōchois</em>) — the disciples\' economic logic is impeccable: the market value was substantial, the poor were ever-present (v.11, "the poor you always have with you"), and almsgiving was the primary expression of covenant faithfulness. John 12:5 specifies the figure at 300 denarii. The disciples have correctly identified the alternative use; what they have missed is the context that makes the present use appropriate.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"But Jesus, aware of this, said to them, \'Why do you trouble the woman? For she has done a beautiful thing to me\'" (<em>kalon ergon ergasato eis eme</em>) — "a beautiful/good deed" (a <em>kalon ergon</em>) is a deed of moral excellence, not merely practical utility. The commendation acknowledges that the woman has understood something the disciples have not: the appropriate response to the eschatological moment. In the OT, anointing with expensive oil was associated with preparation for burial (Ps 45:7 for kings; 2 Chr 16:14 for burials).</p>',
    "11": '<p>"For you always have the poor with you, but you will not always have me" — the echo of Deut 15:11 ("there will never cease to be poor in the land") is not a dismissal of poverty care but a statement of temporal difference. The Deuteronomy passage is itself a strong injunction to care for the poor; Jesus\' citation does not undermine but contextualizes: continuous obligations (the poor) do not preclude singular acts of appropriate love at unique moments. This moment — Jesus present before his death — has a uniqueness that the ongoing obligation to the poor does not.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"In pouring this ointment on my body, she has done it to prepare me for burial" (<em>pros to entaphiasai me</em>) — burial anointing was the final act of honor for the dead: the body was washed and anointed with oil and perfumes (m. Shabbat 23:5). Jesus identifies the anointing proleptically as a burial preparation; the woman may or may not have intended this, but Jesus frames her act as a prophetic deed — she has anointed the one who will die and, because of the rapid sequence of events, will not receive the standard burial anointing (note the women\'s intention to anoint in 28:1).</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Truly, I say to you, wherever this gospel is proclaimed in the whole world, what she has done will also be told in memory of her" — the promise of worldwide memorial is the highest commendation in Matthew\'s Gospel. The anonymous woman receives a more durable legacy than the disciples who objected. The proclamation of the "gospel" (<em>euangelion</em>) — the good news of Jesus\' death and resurrection — will include the story of the one who understood and honored him before his death, while his own inner circle objected.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Then one of the twelve, who was called Judas Iscariot, went to the chief priests" — the immediate juxtaposition with the anointing scene is deliberate: as the woman anoints Jesus for burial with extravagant love, one of the twelve offers his betrayal for payment. The name "Iscariot" is debated: most likely <em>ish-Kerioth</em> (man from Kerioth, a town in Judea — making Judas the only non-Galilean among the twelve), though other etymologies have been proposed.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"And said, \'What will you give me if I deliver him over to you?\' And they paid him thirty pieces of silver" — thirty pieces of silver is explicitly cited in Zech 11:12-13 as the "lordly price" for the shepherd (a bitter ironic valuation). Thirty shekels was also the fixed compensation under Mosaic law for a slave accidentally gored to death by an ox (Exod 21:32). The amount assigns Jesus the legal value of a slave — the lowest human valuation in the Torah\'s economic framework.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"And from that moment he sought an opportunity to betray him" — <em>euzairian</em> (opportunity): Judas does not immediately act but waits for the right occasion, which turns out to be the private moment of Gethsemane away from the Passover crowd. The leaders\' original constraint (not during the feast, v.5) is satisfied by Judas\'s offer: the arrest can happen privately, away from the public. The opportunistic framing raises the question of whether Judas\'s motive was primarily financial, ideological (disillusionment with Jesus\' non-political messianism), or demonic (Luke 22:3; John 13:27).</p>',
    "18": '<p>The arrangement with the unnamed person in the city: "Go into the city to a certain man and say to him, \'The Teacher says, My time is at hand. I will keep the Passover at your house with my disciples\'" — the prior arrangement (the "certain man" knows who "the Teacher" is) follows the same pattern as the Palm Sunday colt arrangement (21:2-3). The phrase "my time is at hand" (<em>ho kairos mou engys estin</em>) uses the same eschatological vocabulary as the Olivet Discourse: the appointed hour has arrived.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"And the disciples did as Jesus had directed them, and they prepared the Passover" — the preparation of the Passover involved slaughtering and roasting a lamb at the temple (Nisan 14 afternoon), procuring unleavened bread, bitter herbs, and the four cups of wine, and preparing the room. The disciples\' exact obedience (as with the Palm Sunday colt, 21:6) signals the careful fulfillment of Jesus\' instruction in a scenario requiring both trust and logistical coordination.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"When it was evening, he reclined at table with the twelve" — the evening timing is significant: the Passover seder by law began after sunset on Nisan 14/15. "Reclined at table" (<em>anekeito meta tōn dōdeka</em>) — formal meal posture in the Greco-Roman world was reclining on couches around a low table (triclinium arrangement). The Mishnah specifies that even the poorest Israelite should recline at the Passover as a sign of freedom, recalling the reclining posture of free people at banquets vs. the standing posture of servants.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"And as they were eating, he said, \'Truly, I say to you, one of you will betray me\'" — the betrayal announcement during the Passover meal intensifies the covenant context: the Passover was the annual reenactment of Israel\'s covenant-foundation event (the Exodus), and covenant betrayal within this meal makes Judas\'s act a covenant violation of the highest order. The announcement is not confrontational but plaintive — "one of you" creates maximum impact precisely because all twelve are present.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"And they were very sorrowful and began to say to him one after another, \'Is it I, Lord?\'" — the question <em>mēti egō eimi, kyrie</em> (surely it is not I, Lord?) uses the Greek particle <em>mēti</em>, which expects a negative answer: "surely not I?" Each disciple asks in self-examination. The form of the question in Greek reveals that none of them knows; the self-doubt is genuine. Judas will ask the same question in v.25, but with an ironic edge that the reader perceives.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"He answered, \'He who has dipped his hand in the dish with me will betray me\'" — dipping bread in a common dish (the charoset or bitter herb sauce of the Passover meal) was the most intimate act of table fellowship in ancient culture. To betray the one with whom you shared the dipping bowl violated the deepest social bond the ancient world recognized. The image echoes Ps 41:9: "Even my close friend in whom I trusted, who ate my bread, has lifted his heel against me."</p>',
    "24": '<p>"The Son of Man goes as it is written of him, but woe to that man by whom the Son of Man is betrayed! It would have been better for that man if he had not been born" — the theological tension here is between divine sovereignty ("as it is written") and human culpability ("woe to that man"). Matthew does not resolve the tension; both are asserted simultaneously. The "as it is written" does not excuse the betrayer; divine foreknowledge of an event does not eliminate the moral agency of the one who performs it.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"Judas, who would betray him, answered, \'Is it I, Rabbi?\'" — Judas uses "Rabbi" (<em>hrabbi</em>) rather than "Lord" (<em>kyrie</em>) as all the other disciples did. The distinction is significant: "Rabbi" is a respectful but purely human title; "Lord" implies the higher authority the other disciples acknowledge. Jesus\' response "You have said so" (<em>su eipas</em>) is a Greek idiom for "the answer is yours" — an affirmation that avoids direct accusation while confirming Judas has spoken correctly. The same formula appears at the trials (v.64; 27:11).</p>',
    "26": '<p>"Now as they were eating, Jesus took bread, and after blessing it broke it and gave it to the disciples, and said, \'Take, eat; this is my body\'" — the eucharistic actions (took, blessed/gave thanks, broke, gave) follow the standard Jewish meal blessing procedure for bread (<em>birkat ha-mazon</em>) and mirror the feeding miracles (14:19; 15:36). Within the Passover context the unleavened bread was already heavy with Exodus symbolism; Jesus now reframes it as his own body. The word <em>soma</em> (body) in Aramaic usage is the whole person, not merely the physical body.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"And he took a cup, and when he had given thanks he gave it to them, saying, \'Drink of it, all of you\'" — the cup is likely the third Passover cup (the "cup of blessing" after the meal, <em>kos shel berakhah</em>), over which the Hallel was sung. Paul identifies "the cup of blessing that we bless" as the cup of koinōnia with Christ\'s blood (1 Cor 10:16), using the same liturgical terminology. "All of you" (<em>pantes</em>) is emphatic: the inclusion is universal for all present.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"For this is my blood of the covenant, which is poured out for many for the forgiveness of sins" — "blood of the covenant" directly echoes Exod 24:8, where Moses sprinkled the covenant blood on the people at Sinai: "Behold the blood of the covenant that the LORD has made with you." The "new covenant" language (explicit in Luke 22:20 and 1 Cor 11:25) draws on Jer 31:31-34. "Poured out for many" (<em>peri pollōn ekchynnomenon</em>) echoes Isa 53:12 (the Servant "poured out his soul to death" and "bore the sin of many"). "For the forgiveness of sins" is Matthew\'s unique addition among the Synoptics.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"I tell you I will not drink again of this fruit of the vine until that day when I drink it new with you in my Father\'s kingdom" — the vow of abstinence connects the Last Supper to the eschatological banquet. In Jewish apocalyptic tradition (1 Enoch 62:14; 2 Bar. 29:5) the messianic age was depicted as a great feast; Jesus promises to resume drinking with the disciples in the fully realized kingdom. The "new" (<em>kainon</em>) wine of the kingdom echoes the new wineskins of 9:17 — a qualitatively transformed reality, not merely a resumption of the old.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"And when they had sung a hymn, they went out to the Mount of Olives" — the Passover seder concluded with the singing of the second half of the Hallel (Ps 115-118 in the Babylonian tradition; Ps 114-118 or 116-118 in other traditions). Psalm 118, with its "blessed is he who comes in the name of the LORD" and "the stone the builders rejected," formed the liturgical bracket around the passion events. The procession from Jerusalem to the Mount of Olives at night would have been common for Passover pilgrims who could not find lodging within the city walls.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"Then Jesus said to them, \'You will all fall away because of me this night. For it is written, \'I will strike the shepherd, and the sheep of the flock will be scattered\'\'" — a citation of Zech 13:7, where YHWH commands the striking of the shepherd. The original context is YHWH\'s judgment on a corrupt shepherd (Zech 13:7-9); Jesus applies it to his own arrest and the disciples\' desertion. "Fall away" (<em>skandalisthēsesthe</em> — will be scandalized, caused to stumble) uses the same verb as the rocky-soil parable: those who initially receive with joy but fall away under tribulation.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"But after I am raised up, I will go before you to Galilee" — the post-resurrection appointment in Galilee (fulfilled in 28:16-20) is announced before the passion begins. The verb "go before" (<em>proago</em>) is the shepherd\'s posture: he leads from the front, and the sheep follow (John 10:4). The resurrection appointment frames the scattering not as a final rupture but as a temporary dispersal that will be gathered again. Galilee, where Jesus\' ministry began, becomes the location of the Great Commission.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"Peter answered him, \'Though they all fall away because of you, I will never fall away\'" — Peter\'s self-differentiation from the group ("though all... I will never") expresses the confident loyalty that flows from genuine devotion but fails to reckon with his own vulnerability. The comparative form — "though all the others..." — actually heightens the irony: Peter\'s denial (vv. 69-74) will be the most detailed of all the disciples\' failures recorded in the passion narrative.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Jesus said to him, \'Truly, I say to you, this very night, before the rooster crows, you will deny me three times\'" — the rooster\'s crow was used as a time marker in Roman Palestine: the Roman night watch divided the night into four watches (evening, midnight, rooster-crow/gallicinium, dawn), and roosters in urban environments crowed in the pre-dawn hours. The specificity of "this very night" and "three times" makes the prediction maximally precise and its fulfillment unmistakable.</p>',
    "35": '<p>"Peter said to him, \'Even if I must die with you, I will not deny you!\' And all the disciples said the same" — all twelve affirm willingness to die with Jesus. The unanimous commitment immediately precedes the universal failure: the disciples\' flight at the arrest (v.56) and Peter\'s three denials (vv. 69-75). Matthew presents this not as hypocrisy but as the gap between sincere intention and actual capacity under pressure — the failure of the disciples is a failure of will, not of initial commitment.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"Then Jesus went with them to a place called Gethsemane (<em>Gethsēmani</em>), and he said to his disciples, \'Sit here, while I go over there and pray\'" — Gethsemane is from the Aramaic <em>gat-shmanim</em> (oil press), referring to an olive orchard with a press on the western slope of the Mount of Olives across the Kidron Valley from Jerusalem. The garden was known to Judas, who had been there with Jesus before (John 18:2), which explains how Judas could lead the arrest party directly to Jesus at night without a lengthy search.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"And taking with him Peter and the two sons of Zebedee, he began to be sorrowful and troubled" — the inner three (Peter, James, and John) who witnessed the Transfiguration (17:1) are brought into the most intimate moment of the passion. The verbs "sorrowful" (<em>lupeisthai</em>) and "troubled" (<em>adēmonein</em>) are both strong emotional terms: <em>adēmonein</em> in particular denotes profound distress, anxiety, and anguish. The Transfiguration scene revealed heavenly glory; Gethsemane reveals the cost of that glory in full humanity.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"Then he said to them, \'My soul is very sorrowful, even to death (<em>perilypos estin hē psychē mou heōs thanatou</em>); remain here, and watch with me\'" — the phrase "sorrowful even to death" echoes the language of Ps 42:5, 11 ("Why are you cast down, O my soul?") and Ps 43:5. The Psalms of lament are the scriptural matrix for Jesus\' anguish. His invitation to "watch with me" is a request for solidarity in suffering — which the disciples will fail to provide. The word "watch" (<em>grēgoreite</em>) connects to the eschatological watchfulness command of 24:42-43 and the ten virgins.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"And going a little farther he fell on his face and prayed, saying, \'My Father, if it be possible, let this cup pass from me; nevertheless, not as I will, but as you will\'" — prostration (<em>epesen epi prosōpon autou</em>) is the standard OT posture for intense supplication before God (Num 20:6; Josh 7:6; Ezek 9:8). The "cup" (<em>potērion</em>) as a metaphor for fate, especially suffering and divine judgment, appears throughout the OT (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17, 22; Jer 25:15-16; Ezek 23:31-34). Jesus does not pray with resignation but with genuine desire for another way; the final clause ("as you will") is the authentic prayer of covenant submission.</p>',
    "40": '<p>"And he came to the disciples and found them sleeping. And he said to Peter, \'So, could you not watch with me one hour?\'" — the specific address to Peter is pointed given Peter\'s confident declaration in v.33. The disciples\' sleep is not culpable inattention but the exhaustion of a late Passover night following a week of intense activity. "One hour" (<em>mian hōran</em>) suggests the duration of Jesus\' first prayer; the Mishnah requires that the seder discussion continue until one falls asleep, but this Passover has extended well past midnight.</p>',
    "41": '<p>"Watch and pray that you may not enter into temptation (<em>peirasmon</em>). The spirit indeed is willing, but the flesh is weak" — the Lord\'s Prayer\'s petition "lead us not into temptation" (<em>mē eisenenkēs eis peirasmon</em>, 6:13) is echoed here in its practical context. "Spirit is willing, flesh is weak" acknowledges the genuine gap between the will\'s intention and the body\'s capacity, without making this an excuse. The disciples\' failure at Gethsemane is the very failure the Lord\'s Prayer was designed to address; they have not done the watching they were instructed to do.</p>',
    "42": '<p>"Again, for the second time, he went away and prayed, \'My Father, if this cannot pass unless I drink it, your will be done\'" — the second prayer moves from "if possible, let it pass" to "if this cannot pass unless I drink it, your will be done." The progression is not resignation but active alignment: Jesus\' own will is being brought into conformity with the Father\'s. "Your will be done" (<em>genēthētō to thelēma sou</em>) is the exact wording of the Lord\'s Prayer (6:10), prayed now in the most consequential context.</p>',
    "43": '<p>"And again he came and found them sleeping, for their eyes were heavy" (<em>bebarēmenoi gar autōn hoi ophthalmoi</em>) — the heaviness of their eyes is a detail of sympathetic realism: it is late at night, possibly 2-3am, after an emotionally and physically exhausting week. The Greek <em>bebarēmenoi</em> (weighed down) is the same vocabulary used for the disciples\' incomprehension at the Transfiguration (Luke 9:32: "heavy with sleep"). The repeated failure underscores their human limitations.</p>',
    "44": '<p>"So, leaving them again, he went away and prayed for the third time, saying the same words again" — three prayers with the disciples sleeping between each: the structure mirrors the three denials to follow (vv. 69-75). Both Jesus\' intercession and Peter\'s denial are repeated three times, the prayer in the garden and the denial in the courtyard forming a dark structural parallel. Jesus\' third prayer is noted without content — "saying the same words again" — emphasizing persistence in prayer rather than innovative pleading.</p>',
    "45": '<p>"Then he came to the disciples and said to them, \'Sleep and take your rest later on. See, the hour is at hand, and the Son of Man is betrayed into the hands of sinners\'" — "sleep and take your rest later on" (<em>katheudete to loipon kai anapaeisthe</em>) may be interrogative ("are you sleeping and resting?") or a resigned permission ("sleep now if you wish"). Either way, "see, the hour is at hand" terminates the watching period. The "hour" (<em>hōra</em>) is the eschatological hour of the passion, anticipated throughout the Gospel (cf. John 12:23, 27).</p>',
    "46": '<p>"Rise, let us be going; see, my betrayer is at hand" — <em>Egeiresthe agōmen</em> (Rise, let us go) is a command of active engagement, not resignation. Jesus does not wait to be arrested but moves toward the approaching party. This voluntary movement toward the arrest is the first act of his freely chosen suffering: he could have fled into the night (the disciples expected him to, evidently, given their eventual flight) but instead advances to meet those who come for him.</p>',
    "47": '<p>"While he was still speaking, Judas came, one of the twelve, and with him a great crowd with swords and clubs, from the chief priests and the elders of the people" — the "great crowd with swords and clubs" sent by the chief priests and elders is likely the temple guard (Levitical police who maintained order in the temple precincts, under the high priest\'s authority) rather than Roman soldiers. John 18:3 mentions a <em>speira</em> (Roman cohort), though this may be hyperbolic or refer to a Roman officer accompanying the Jewish force as liaison.</p>',
    "48": '<p>"Now the betrayer had given them a sign, saying, \'The one I will kiss is the man; seize him\'" — in the darkness of the garden at night, identifying the right person from a group required a signal. The kiss (<em>philēma</em>) was the standard greeting between a student and his rabbi — a kiss on the hand or cheek signifying honor and affection. Judas weaponizes this intimate gesture of discipleship to identify Jesus to the arrest party. The cultural inversion — the teacher-greeting becomes a death-mark — is the act\'s full horror.</p>',
    "49": '<p>"And he came up to Jesus at once and said, \'Greetings, Rabbi!\' and kissed him" — <em>Chaire, hrabbi</em> (Hail/Greetings, Rabbi!) is the ordinary greeting formula. The word <em>katephilēsen</em> (kissed warmly/repeatedly) in Mark 14:45 may intensify the kiss — an effusive greeting that performed genuine affection while executing betrayal. The politeness of the greeting in the moment of arrest is the parable of hypocrisy enacted; the formal expression of love functions as its opposite.</p>',
    "50": '<p>"Jesus said to him, \'Friend, do what you came to do\'" (<em>Hetaire, eph\' ho parei</em>) — <em>hetaire</em> (friend, companion) is the formal address Jesus has used to the grumbling vineyard worker (20:13) and the ungarmented wedding guest (22:12) — each time carrying a note of gentle but firm reproach to someone acting against the relationship\'s spirit. "Do what you came to do" (<em>eph\' ho parei</em>) may be rendered as a question ("For what purpose have you come?") or as Jesus\' release of Judas to complete his act. Either way, Jesus names the moment with calm authority.</p>',
    "51": '<p>"And behold, one of those who were with Jesus stretched out his hand and drew his sword and struck the servant of the high priest and cut off his ear" — John 18:10 identifies the sword-drawer as Peter and the servant as Malchus. The ear-cutting is a common wound in ancient combat accounts: a blow intended for the head or neck, partially deflected. The crowd\'s possession of weapons was not unusual; many Passover pilgrims carried arms in the volatile environment of occupied Jerusalem. Jesus\' immediate healing of the ear (Luke 22:51) is Matthew\'s focus moved to the theological principle in v.52.</p>',
    "52": '<p>"Then Jesus said to him, \'Put your sword back into its place. For all who take the sword will perish by the sword\'" — a general principle of retributive violence, not a pacifist absolute. In context, it addresses the specific situation: armed resistance to the arrest would trigger Roman counter-measures that would destroy the disciples and Jesus\'s movement. The principle also reflects the logic of Ps 7:16; Prov 8:36: violence generates escalating counter-violence. Jesus\' arrest will not be resisted by force because his kingdom does not advance by the sword (cf. John 18:36).</p>',
    "53": '<p>"Do you think that I cannot appeal to my Father, and he will at once send me more than twelve legions of angels?" — a Roman legion comprised approximately 6,000 soldiers. Twelve legions is 72,000 soldiers — one legion for each disciple (perhaps intentionally symbolic). The appeal to angelic armies echoes the angelic hosts who defend God\'s people in the OT (2 Kgs 6:17; Dan 10:13, 20; 12:1). The rhetorical question exposes the voluntary nature of the arrest: Jesus\' submission is not weakness but the deliberate choice not to invoke available power.</p>',
    "54": '<p>"But how then should the Scriptures be fulfilled, that it must be so?" — the constraint that prevents the call for angelic rescue is not incapacity but scripture. The "must" (<em>dei</em>) of the passion is a consistent Matthean and Lukan theme (16:21; 17:12): the Messiah\'s suffering is scripturally necessary, not merely historically contingent. The specific scriptures in view are not named here, but the passion narrative as a whole constitutes a dense tissue of OT fulfillments (Psalms of lament, Isaiah\'s Servant Songs, Zechariah\'s shepherd).</p>',
    "55": '<p>"At that hour Jesus said to the crowds, \'Have you come out as against a robber, with swords and clubs to capture me? Day after day I sat in the temple teaching, and you did not seize me\'" — the public teaching in the temple (21:23-23:39) provided ample opportunity for arrest in visible circumstances. The nocturnal armed expedition is exposed as a preference for concealment over legal process, confirming the leaders\' self-serving reading of the situation. "As against a robber" (<em>lēstēn</em>) — a <em>lēstēs</em> was a brigand or violent revolutionary; Jesus\' teaching in the temple required no armed response.</p>',
    "56": '<p>"But all this has taken place that the Scriptures of the prophets might be fulfilled" (<em>hina plērōthōsin hai graphai tōn prophētōn</em>) — the passion events are framed as scripture fulfillment, not merely historical events. "Then all the disciples left him and fled" — the prediction of v.31 (Zech 13:7: the sheep scattered at the shepherd\'s striking) is fulfilled immediately. The disciples\' flight is not recorded as a moral failure here but as a fulfillment of the prophetic word — though both are true simultaneously.</p>',
    "57": '<p>"Then those who had seized Jesus led him to Caiaphas the high priest, where the scribes and the elders had gathered" — Caiaphas (high priest ca. 18-36 CE) presided over the Sanhedrin, the supreme Jewish council of 71 members. The nocturnal gathering is legally irregular: later Mishnaic regulations (m. Sanhedrin 4:1) prohibited capital trials at night and required a second session the next day for sentencing. Whether these rules were in force in 30 CE is debated; the irregularity may indicate the leaders\' urgency rather than formal illegality.</p>',
    "58": '<p>"And Peter was following him at a distance, as far as the courtyard of the high priest, and going inside he sat with the guards to see the end" — Peter\'s following "at a distance" (<em>makrothen</em>) is both geographic description and spiritual metaphor: he has not completely abandoned Jesus but maintains a safe remove. The <em>aule</em> (courtyard) of the high priest\'s house was a common gathering area for servants and guards; Peter\'s presence there is a realistic detail of Palestinian domestic architecture.</p>',
    "59": '<p>"Now the chief priests and the whole council were seeking false testimony against Jesus that they might put him to death" — the Sanhedrin trial as Matthew presents it is not a genuine judicial inquiry but a verdict-first process: the death decision has been made (26:4) and witnesses are sought to confirm it. The requirement of witnesses reflects the Torah\'s capital case procedure (Deut 17:6; 19:15); the leaders are observing the procedural form while corrupting its substance. The description "false testimony" (<em>pseudomartyrian</em>) is Matthew\'s explicit editorial judgment.</p>',
    "60": '<p>"But they found none, though many false witnesses came forward. At last two came forward" — the inability to find consistent testimony despite numerous witnesses illustrates the essential problem with the case: Jesus had not violated Torah law in a way that supported a capital charge. The eventual charge (the temple saying of v.61) was itself a misquotation that contradicted the actual witnesses among themselves (Mark 14:59: "their testimony did not agree").</p>',
    "61": '<p>"And said, \'This man said, \'I am able to destroy the temple of God, and to rebuild it in three days\'\'" — a garbled version of John 2:19 ("Destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up"), where Jesus speaks of his own body (John 2:21). The temple saying was remembered in distorted form; the witnesses present it as a statement about the physical Jerusalem temple, which would indeed constitute a threat against the holy place — a capital offense under Herodian and Roman law. The irony is that the misquoted version becomes the false charge; the actual saying, rightly understood, is the Gospel\'s central claim.</p>',
    "62": '<p>"And the high priest stood up and said, \'Have you no answer to make? What is it that these men testify against you?\'" — the high priest\'s intervention signals that the formal witness phase has not produced adequate grounds for condemnation. Standing up is a gesture of judicial authority and procedural urgency. Caiaphas moves directly to interrogating Jesus about the specific charge, which forces Jesus to respond to claims he has not directly confirmed.</p>',
    "63": '<p>"But Jesus remained silent. And the high priest said to him, \'I adjure you by the living God, tell us if you are the Christ, the Son of God\'" — Jesus\' silence before the false witnesses echoes Isa 53:7 ("He was oppressed, and he was afflicted, yet he opened not his mouth"). The formal oath (<em>exorkizō se kata tou theou tou zōntos</em>) invokes the highest legal compulsion: to remain silent under formal oath in a Jewish court would constitute contempt of the divine name. The high priest has correctly identified the real question: messianic identity.</p>',
    "64": '<p>"Jesus said to him, \'You have said so. But I tell you, from now on you will see the Son of Man seated at the right hand of Power and coming on the clouds of heaven\'" — <em>su eipas</em> (you have said so): the same formula as v.25 and 27:11, confirming the statement without simple "yes." "Power" (<em>hē dynamis</em>) is a Jewish circumlocution for God: the divine name was too sacred to use in contexts that might risk profanation, so "Power," "Heaven," and "the Blessed" served as respectful alternatives. The combined citation of Ps 110:1 (right hand of God) and Dan 7:13 (coming on the clouds) is the messianic claim in its fullest form.</p>',
    "65": '<p>"Then the high priest tore his robes and said, \'He has uttered blasphemy. What further witnesses do we need?\'" — the tearing of the high priest\'s robes (<em>dierēxen ta himatia autou</em>) was the prescribed response upon hearing blasphemy (m. Sanhedrin 7:5): it both expressed horror and, by rendering the garment unfit for further sacred use, publicly marked the moment as a formal blasphemy event. The procedural need for witnesses is now declared fulfilled: the defendant has uttered blasphemy before the court. This short-circuits the formal witness requirement by making the confession itself the evidence.</p>',
    "66": '<p>"What is your judgment?" They answered, "He deserves death" (<em>enochos thanatou estin</em>) — the formal verdict of the Sanhedrin. Under Roman provincial administration, the Sanhedrin retained jurisdiction over religious matters but had lost the power to execute capital sentences (John 18:31: "It is not lawful for us to put anyone to death"). The religious verdict must be converted into a Roman charge — hence the transfer to Pilate and the reframing of the charge from blasphemy (a Jewish religious offense) to claiming to be king of the Jews (a political offense against Roman sovereignty).</p>',
    "67": '<p>"Then they spit in his face and struck him. And some slapped him, saying, \'Prophesy to us, you Christ! Who is it that struck you?\'" — the mistreatment during the night session precedes the formal Roman proceedings. The specific mockery — "prophesy to us who struck you" (while blindfolded, Mark 14:65) — is a taunt directed at the messianic claim, since the expected Messiah was believed to have special knowledge. The treatment echoes Isa 50:6 (the Servant: "I gave my back to those who strike, and my cheeks to those who pull out the beard; I hid not my face from disgrace and spitting").</p>',
    "68": '<p>"\'Prophesy to us, you Christ! Who is it that struck you?\'" — the mockery\'s irony is that the one they mock for failing to identify his tormentors has just, in the same session, made the most consequential identification in the Gospel\'s narrative: declaring himself the Son of Man at the right hand of Power. The failure to perceive this identification while demanding a cheap demonstration of prophetic gift is the essence of the leaders\' blindness throughout Matthew.</p>',
    "69": '<p>"Now Peter was sitting outside in the courtyard. And a servant girl came up to him and said, \'You also were with Jesus the Galilean\'" — the courtyard scene is spatially separate from the trial before Caiaphas. Peter has positioned himself to observe "the end" (v.58) while maintaining deniability. The servant girl (<em>paidiskē</em>) is a domestic slave — the lowest-status person in the household hierarchy. That Peter denies before such a person, not before the high priest or soldiers, underscores the social dimensions of his failure: he cannot sustain his loyalty even to those who pose no real threat.</p>',
    "70": '<p>"But he denied it before them all, saying, \'I do not know what you mean\'" — the first denial is a denial of comprehension rather than direct identity denial: "I don\'t know what you\'re talking about." This is the most evasive form: neither confirming nor directly denying. The form of denial escalates with each iteration, from comprehension-denial to identity-denial to oath-sworn identity-denial.</p>',
    "71": '<p>"And when he went out to the entrance, another servant girl saw him, and she said to the bystanders, \'This man was with Jesus of Nazareth\'" — Peter retreats from the main courtyard to the gateway area, perhaps hoping to leave, but a second accuser finds him. The identification "Jesus of Nazareth" adds the geographic specificity that makes the association concrete. The bystanders now become an audience for the second denial, raising the social pressure.</p>',
    "72": '<p>"And again he denied it with an oath: \'I do not know the man\'" — the second denial adds an oath (<em>meta horkou</em>), invoking divine witness for the denial. The irony of Peter using the oath-structure — given Jesus\' teaching against oaths in 5:33-37 — underlines the disintegration of his discipleship. "I do not know the man" (<em>ouk oida ton anthrōpon</em>) is more categorical than the first denial, explicitly denying knowledge of the person rather than the question.</p>',
    "73": '<p>"After a little while the bystanders came up and said to Peter, \'Certainly you too are one of them, for your accent betrays you\'" — Galilean Aramaic had a distinctive dialect: the Galileans dropped guttural consonants, producing recognizable speech differences from Judean speech patterns (documented in b. Eruvin 53b; b. Megillah 24b). The phonological difference was audible enough to provide confident identification: Peter\'s Galilean accent marks him as a northerner associated with the Galilean teacher who has just been condemned.</p>',
    "74": '<p>"Then he began to invoke a curse on himself and to swear, \'I do not know the man.\' And immediately the rooster crowed" — the third denial adds self-cursing (<em>katathematizein heauton</em>, calling down destruction on himself if he lies) to the oath, escalating to the most emphatic possible denial. The rooster crow immediately follows — the night\'s time-marker fulfilling Jesus\' prediction of v.34 down to the hour. The three denials (servant girl, another servant girl + bystanders, bystanders with accent-accusation) correspond to three social levels of pressure.</p>',
    "75": '<p>"And Peter remembered the saying of Jesus, \'Before the rooster crows, you will deny me three times.\' And he went out and wept bitterly" — <em>Eklausen pikrōs</em> (he wept bitterly): the adverb <em>pikrōs</em> (bitterly, with painful intensity) is used elsewhere for the most acute grief. The remembrance and the weeping are the difference between Judas\'s remorse (27:3, same word <em>metamelomai</em>) and Peter\'s repentance: both grieve, but Peter\'s grief will lead to restoration (John 21:15-17) while Judas\'s will lead to destruction. The contrast is Matthew\'s implicit pastoral theology of repentance vs. despair.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew')
    merge_comm(existing, MATTHEW)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'matthew', existing)
    print('Matthew 26 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
